							h2 Description
							p The McClellan oscillator is a market breadth indicator based in the number of stocks that closed higher (advances) and that closed lower (declines) in the New York Stock Exchange. 
							p Developed by Sherman and Marian McClellan in 1969, the oscillator is computed using the exponential moving average (EMA) of the daily ordinal difference of advancing issues (stocks which gained in value) from declining issues (stocks which fell in value) over 39 trading day and 19 trading day periods.

			div(class="row row-tiles")
				div.col-md-12
